Maybe `database` would be even better... `database` -> `name` -> `type` (imho).
```
sql {
    database = 'MySQLdb'
    format = '{placeholder1} {placeholder2} {placeholder3}'
    query = 'SELECT * FROM ...'
    parameters = {
        'host': 'empty',
        'passwd': 'empty',
    }
}

Actually, this was left from before. I just forgot to clean it up. I will remove it now

Not used anywhere. All conversions are in export_import.rs

fn u64_to_bytes(u: u64) -> [u8; 8] {
    let u = u.to_be();
    let res: [u8; 8] = unsafe { mem::transmute(u) };
    res
}

fn u32_to_bytes(u: u32) -> [u8; 4] {
    let u = u.to_be();
    let res: [u8; 4] = unsafe { mem::transmute(u) };
    res
}

fn u16_to_bytes(u: u16) -> [u8; 2] {
    let u = u.to_be();
    let res: [u8; 2] = unsafe { mem::transmute(u) };
    res
}

Actually, I'd recommend against this change: it's TensorFlow convention to take optional arguments as `None` and, if necessary, set `if foo is None: foo = default_foo` within the code. This has the distinct advantage that it is always safe to pass `foo=None` to mean "use the default value," as opposed to having

```
def function(foo="DEFAULT"):
  pass

def caller(foo="DEFAULT"):
   function(foo=foo)

def grandcaller(foo="DEFAULT"):
  caller(foo=foo)
```
which both leaks implementation details of the default value and leaves the code much more fragile to changes.

(There are other benefits to `foo=None`, like consistent mutable-default-value initialization.)
